What

Encapsulation is the practice of protecting and organizing code inside a class.

Why

It prevents accidental changes of internal data

How

By using access modifiers—making fields private and exposing controlled access through public getters and setters.

class User {
    private String email;

    public String getEmail() {
        return email;
    }
}

General-Knowledge/Java/4.-OOP-Concepts/2.content:
What

Inheritance lets a class reuse code from another class or interface.


extends → inherit from a parent class


implements → inherit method signatures from an interface



Why

To reuse code, follow a contract, and allow polymorphism while keeping design clean and scalable.

How



Use extends to inherit fields and methods from a parent class.


Use implements to adopt abstract methods from one or more interfaces.



class Animal { void eat() {} }
interface Flyable { void fly(); }

class Bird extends Animal implements Flyable {
    public void fly() { System.out.println(&quot;Bird flies&quot;); }
}

Bird inherits eat() from Animal and must implement fly() from Flyable.

General-Knowledge/Java/4.-OOP-Concepts/3.content:
What

Polymorphism allows objects to take multiple forms; allows objects respond differently to the same method call (depending on their actual type on runtime)

Why

To write flexible, reusable, and scalable code.

**How


Compile-time (Method Overloading)

Same method name with different parameters within the same class.



Runtime (Method Overriding)


Same method name and parameters in subclasses or implementing classes.


Applies to:


Parent → Child class: Subclass overrides a method from the parent.


Abstract class → Concrete class: Concrete class provides implementation for abstract methods.


Interface → Implementing class: Class implements interface methods.






// Overloading example
class MathUtil {
    int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
    double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }
}

// Overriding example
class Animal { void sound() { System.out.println(&quot;Some sound&quot;); } }
class Dog extends Animal { void sound() { System.out.println(&quot;Bark&quot;); } }

Animal a = new Dog();
a.sound(); // Outputs &quot;Bark&quot; – runtime polymorphism

General-Knowledge/Java/4.-OOP-Concepts/4.content:
What

Abstraction hides implementation details and shows only essential behavior.

Why

To reduce complexity and improve maintainability.

How

Achieved by:

Abstract classes
Interfaces


Abstract Class
What it is:

A class that cannot be instantiated directly.
Can have both abstract methods (without body) and concrete methods (with implementation).

When to use:

When classes share common behavior or state (fields).
When you want to provide default behavior for subclasses.

abstract class Vehicle {
    int speed;
    abstract void move();

    void start() { System.out.println(&quot;Vehicle started&quot;); }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    void move() { System.out.println(&quot;Car is moving&quot;); }
}

Can have fields, constructors, and default method implementations.

Interface
What it is:
Historically, interfaces were like strict abstract classes: they could only declare method signatures and constants, forcing implementing classes to provide behavior. In modern Java, interfaces can also include default and static methods, which allow some shared implementation while still defining a contract.
The key difference from abstract classes:

is that interfaces cannot have instance fields,
a class can implement multiple interfaces, achieving multiple inheritance of type.


A contract defining method signatures only (until Java 8, interfaces could not have default methods).
Classes implement the interface and provide concrete behavior.

When to use:

To define capabilities a class should have.
To achieve multiple inheritance of type, because Java does not allow multiple class inheritance.

interface Flyable {
    void fly();
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
}

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {
    public void fly() { System.out.println(&quot;Duck flies&quot;); }
    public void swim() { System.out.println(&quot;Duck swims&quot;); }
}


Cannot have instance fields, only constants (static final), but can have default and static methods in modern Java.

Key Differences



































