General-Knowledge/Java/Random-Questions/.content:
Java allows a class to implement multiple interfaces because interfaces are pure contracts — they only define method signatures (behavior), not state (fields).
How it avoids the diamond problem


Diamond problem: happens in multiple class inheritance when a class inherits the same method from multiple parents, creating ambiguity.


Interfaces avoid this because:


They cannot have instance fields, so there is no conflicting state.


Their methods are abstract (or default), so the implementing class decides the actual behavior, removing ambiguity.




interface A { void show(); }
interface B { void show(); }

class C implements A, B {
    public void show() { System.out.println(&quot;Implemented in C&quot;); }
}

What happens when both interfaces has default implementation?
interface A {
    default void show() { System.out.println(&quot;A&#039;s show&quot;); }
}

interface B {
    default void show() { System.out.println(&quot;B&#039;s show&quot;); }
}

class C implements A, B {
    public void show() { System.out.println(&quot;Implemented in C&quot;); }
}


Both interfaces A and B define default methods with the same signature.
If C does not override show(), the compiler will throw an error, because Java does not know which default method to inherit.
This is Java’s way of handling the diamond problem for default methods.

What happens if only interface a has a default?
interface A {
    default void show() { System.out.println(&quot;A&#039;s show&quot;); }
}

interface B {
    void show(); // abstract method (no default)
}

class C implements A, B {
    // No override here
}


Class C inherits the default implementation from A.
No compiler error occurs because there is no conflict — only one default exists.
So C can just use A’s default show() without overriding.
Optional Overriding: C can still override show() if it wants its own behavior

“== checks if two references point to the same object; equals() checks if two objects have the same content.”
== operator
What

Checks if two references point to the exact same object in memory.

Why

Use == when you want to know if two variables refer to the same object, not whether their content is the same.

How / Example
String a = new String(&quot;Java&quot;);
String b = new String(&quot;Java&quot;);

System.out.println(a == b);  // false → different objects
System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true → same content


## Works for primitives
int x = 5;
int y = 5;
System.out.println(x == y); // true → compares values

equals() method
What

Checks if two objects are logically “equal”, i.e., their content is the same.

Why

Use equals() when you want value/content comparison rather than reference comparison.

How / Example
String s1 = new String(&quot;Java&quot;);
String s2 = new String(&quot;Java&quot;);

System.out.println(s1.equals(s2)); // true → content is same

Note: Some classes (like String, Integer) override equals() to compare content.
Custom classes should override equals() if you want logical equality.
class Person {
    String name;
    Person(String name) { this.name = name; }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if(this == obj) return true;
        if(obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
        return name.equals(((Person)obj).name);
    }
}

Person p1 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);
Person p2 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);
System.out.println(p1.equals(p2)); // true → content-based equality

If you don’t override equals()

Every class in Java implicitly extends Object.
Object has a default equals() method:

public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    return this == obj;  // checks reference equality
}

That means, by default, equals() behaves exactly like == — it only checks if the two references point to the same object, not whether their content is equal.
What happens in your example if you remove equals() override ?
class Person {
    String name;
    Person(String name) { this.name = name; }
}

Person p1 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);
Person p2 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);

System.out.println(p1.equals(p2)); // false
System.out.println(p1 == p2);      // false

“In Java, if you override equals() to compare object content, you must also override hashCode(). This ensures that hash-based collections like HashMap and HashSet can locate objects correctly. Objects that are equal must have the same hash code.”
What is hashCode()

hashCode() is a method in Java that returns an integer representing the object’s memory-based hash.

Used by hash-based collections like HashMap, HashSet, HashTable.
Helps locate objects quickly in hash tables.


Person p = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;); System.out.println(p.hashCode()); // some integer
Why hashCode() matters

If you override equals() but don’t override hashCode(), hash-based collections break.

Example:
class Person {
    String name;
    Person(String name) { this.name = name; }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if(this == obj) return true;
        if(obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
        return name.equals(((Person)obj).name);
    }
}

Person p1 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);
Person p2 = new Person(&quot;Alice&quot;);

HashSet&lt;Person&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
set.add(p1);
System.out.println(set.contains(p2)); // false if hashCode not overridden

Why?

HashSet first checks the hash code to find the “bucket”
Then calls equals() to check equality
If hashCode() is not overridden, p1 and p2 may have different hashes, so contains fails, even though equals() returns true

How to fix it

Always override both equals() and hashCode() when defining logical equality

@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return name.hashCode();  // hash based on relevant fields
}


Now HashSet and HashMap work correctly:

HashSet&lt;Person&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
set.add(p1);
System.out.println(set.contains(p2)); // true
